# Bit.Hub telemetry ‚Äúbiteration‚Äù: turning GitHub‚Äôs collector idea into your own .bit mesh

You can‚Äôt (and shouldn‚Äôt) post to GitHub‚Äôs internal endpoint at https://collector.github.com/github/collect. Instead, you‚Äôll stand up your own Bit.Hub collector and ‚Äúbiterate‚Äù telemetry across your workflows via a tiny, signed HTTP protocol. Below is a complete, working pattern you can drop into Bit.Hub:

- A portable collector service (FastAPI) with HMAC request verification
- A composite GitHub Action to emit events safely
- A schema and config under .bit/
- Integration hooks for your governed CI/CD, policy gate, and auto‚Äërepair
- A policy rule that enforces ‚Äútelemetry present‚Äù in workflows

Everything is fail‚Äëopen for tooling hiccups, but hard on integrity (signatures, masking, scrubbed payloads).

---

## Architecture

- Emitters: jobs/steps call a local composite action ‚Äúbit-emit-telemetry,‚Äù which:
  - Builds a JSON payload (no secrets), scrubs env, adds GitHub context
  - Signs it with HMAC-SHA256 using a per‚Äëorg secret
  - POSTs to your collector URL with signature header
  - Fails open on network/tooling, never blocks your pipeline

- Collector: a small service (FastAPI) validates signature, checks schema, timestamps and stores the event (S3/minio, disk, or a message queue). Optional OTLP export for OpenTelemetry.

- Policy: workflow.rego enforces that each workflow has at least one telemetry emission step per job.

